Author: lukas85#6738
Content: @OceanGPT Why does Ocean Protocol use the blockchain?

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content: For both providers and consumers of data, blockchain is a superior substrate for building applications. Blockchain allows business logic to be instantiated in a network and triggered by the users, without intermediaries. This innovation promises lower transaction costs, higher security, more control, less errors and more transparency & auditability. However, Ocean Protocol also implements access control and encryption to ensure that only authorized parties can access the data.

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content: ain idea behind Compute-to-Data is to enable the use of private data without actually sharing it. This is achieved by allowing third parties to run specific compute jobs on the data owner's premises, without ever accessing the data directly. This way, the data owner can monetize their data assets while preserving privacy and control over their data. Compute-to-Data is a powerful tool for data sharing in science and technology contexts, as well as for companies looking to monetize their data assets.

Content: @OceanGPT how can i use ocean protocol compute to data to run computation on a private data set that i own?

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content: s Compute-to-Data feature allows you to sell compute access to your privately-held data without actually sharing the data itself. To use this feature, you would need to deploy a new ERC721 and ERC20 datatoken contract for each data service, then mint datatokens. You can then transfer these datatokens to another owner or approve and transfer them using ERC20 support in web3.js, web3.py, and Solidity. Additionally, you can use Ocean to publish and access data services, either as downloadable files or compute-to-data. You can also use private docker registry, datasets and algorithms, and a minikube environment to write algorithms and leverage the entire ecosystem. For a deeper understanding of how Compute-to-Data works, you can refer to the Architecture, Datasets & Algorithms, Minikube Environment, Writing Algorithms, and Private docker registry guides.

Author: doteth
Content: @OceanGPT What is data farming?

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content:
Data farming refers to the process of earning rewards by locking OCEAN tokens and allocating veOCEAN tokens to Ocean Market projects. It involves two types of rewards: passive rewards and active rewards.

Passive rewards are generated when users lock their OCEAN tokens for a specific period of time. In return, they receive veOCEAN tokens. The quantity of veOCEAN tokens determines the amount of weekly OCEAN rewards the user can accumulate. These rewards are called "passive" because they are generated automatically without human intervention. Users can claim their OCEAN rewards every Thursday on the Rewards page.

To participate in data farming and earn veOCEAN tokens, users need to navigate to the veOCEAN page. They can lock their OCEAN tokens by selecting the "Lock OCEAN, get veOCEAN" panel on the right side of the page. By connecting a wallet, users can see their OCEAN token balance and select a lock end date. The more OCEAN tokens locked or the longer the lock period, the higher the rewards. After confirming the transaction, the OCEAN tokens are locked in exchange for veOCEAN tokens. The veOCEAN balance can be seen in the "My veOCEAN" panel.

Active rewards are earned when users allocate their veOCEAN tokens to Ocean Market projects. These rewards are based on the sales of the projects. Unlike passive rewards, active rewards require human intervention to decide the allocations. Users can allocate their veOCEAN tokens by clicking the "Set Allocations" button on the Active Rewards panel. The more veOCEAN tokens allocated, the higher the potential rewards.

In summary, data farming involves locking OCEAN tokens to earn veOCEAN tokens and then allocating those veOCEAN tokens to Ocean Market projects to earn weekly OCEAN rewards.

Content:
I'm sorry for the confusion, but as an AI text-based model, I'm unable to create or design images. However, I can describe how you might design an image showing the blockchain nodes connected to each other.

1. **Nodes**: Start by drawing several circles (or squares, if you prefer) scattered across your image. These represent the nodes in the blockchain network. You might want to label them as "Node 1", "Node 2", etc. for clarity.

2. **Connections**: Draw lines connecting these nodes to each other. These lines represent the connections between nodes in the blockchain network. In a decentralized blockchain, each node is connected to every other node.

3. **Blockchain**: Inside each node, you could draw a chain of blocks to represent the blockchain that each node maintains. Each block in the chain could be represented by a smaller square or rectangle.

4. **Transactions**: If you want to represent transactions, you could draw arrows along the lines between nodes. These arrows would represent the transfer of information (or cryptocurrency, in the case of networks like Bitcoin) between nodes.

5. **Colors and Labels**: Use different colors to represent different types of nodes (if applicable), and add labels to clarify what each part of your image represents.

Remember, this is just a basic representation. The actual structure of a blockchain network can get much more complex, especially when you start considering things like mining nodes, full nodes, and lightweight (SPV) nodes.

Content: Generating something hopefully smart, give me a moment...

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content: No, Ocean Protocol cannot use the data provided by providers in the marketplace to form a database to build their own AI. Ocean Protocol is designed to facilitate the sharing and selling of data in a secure and privacy-preserving manner. The data shared on the platform remains under the control of the original data provider. Ocean Protocol itself does not have access to the data unless it is purchased and shared by the data provider. The protocol is built on the principles of data privacy and user control, so it would be against its principles to use the data for its own purposes without explicit permission.

- RealDataWhale = dApp/mobile App skills, community
- DataUnion = dApp skills PLUS Data Union skills, as in: what makes the most valuable data SETS, on micro (individual) and on macro (aggregated , compare above: 2 million social media users) level

- WeDataNation = Also around Millenial/GenZ narrative, with stronger Data Union focus and background, complementary, yet also slightly different from The Data Shift, European focus (both just fuzzy allocation, contintents, but important)
- DataLatte = experienced in the field of creating self-service tools for data supply from retail platforms, Netflix
- FELTtoken = deep machine learning <-> compute to data skills, as in: what would be the most valuable/efficient data-APIs for eg social media platforms in this example?

Author: mantisclone
Content:
> unlimited use of training data for a period of time
This is possible using datatokens and wouldn't require the data nft owner to relinquish control of the data nft. When creating the datatoken, specify the `timeout` to be the number of seconds that a given order is valid for. The dataset or algorithm can then be consumed or used for compute-to-data as many times as the consumer wants until the timeout is reached.

> Or to try monetize the data on your behalf?
I could imagine a professional service that runs ocean infrastructure on behalf of a data publisher. This would certainly require some off-chain coordination and trust, but could still be accomplished using datatokens. The datatoken's `service_endpoint` could point to a provider instance run by the ocean infrastructure provider.  The infrastructure provider would collect provider fees while the data nft owner collects order fees.

Author: Timothy.AthenaProtocol.Eth#2384
Content:
I thought I'd come by and share something pretty exciting that we have been working on over the past few months. 

Athena Protocol is a member organization and founder of dMeter, a dao for the creation of open standards in MRV ( monitoring reporting and verification ) for ESG. This organization has begun to develop its system of governance of these open standards, and Athena Protocol is leading the Engineering Circle, helping to bring adoption of Ocean Protocol Tools and softwares. Our work creating signed claims and comments for the ocean stack has prepared us to compose our middleware's into a data transaction and verification layer capable of conducting audits and certifying ecosystem services. We have a list of organizations planing to integrate with our middleware. 

One organization Im very excited to announce in particular participating in the integrations is the Regen Network ! They will be modifying their attestations to accept IPFS hashes, as well as working with us to develop a shared meta-data schema for v2 of our contracts.  v2 will include geospatial indicators for data assets for easy spatial searches and more!

Author: swish24_08
Content: basically C2D pairs some datasets with an algorithm so that the user never sees the raw data just what the algorithm generates. Ideally you review the algorithms that are allowed on your dataset so that it doesn't just return it. This can work with static datasets and you can team up with someone that creates the algorithm so that both of you can profit. The best use case is with dynamic data (that updates constantly) so the user need to start a c2d job each week or each month depending on how fast the data updates.

Author: jamie123abc
Content:
I'm not sure I fully understand what you are trying to do here? Barge deploys the ocean contracts on ganache and then starts up the other ocean components in docker containers. When you say, "connect to a different ethereum RPC provider" it sounds like you are trying to use a different network? 

If your intention is to use a different testnet, I would highly recommend that you use one of the testnets that we are already deployed to - such as goeli or Mumbai. Barge is not a tool for deploying the contracts to other networks. Normally all contract deployments are handled by the core team.

Author: carmina19
Content: Hello @alex, if you use barge, the contracts are deployed locally on ganache/development network and you need to export the address file (because for ganache the addresses are not persistent) like this `export ADDRESS_FILE=~/.ocean/ocean-contracts/artifacts/address.json`. If you want to use a remote network, you do not need barge.

Author: Norbert | Ocean#7805
Content: Great!

Author: feno1486
Content: Please tell me how can I make my prediction? The bot is running, continuously updated, but I don’t see in the instructions how to make a predictions?

Author: Norbert | Ocean#7805
Content: You don't have to do anything. If the prediction window it's getting close to be closed, it's going to submit the prediction for you. For example, if you predict 5m timeframe, ~20s before current timeframe is ended it's going to submit.

Author: feno1486
Content: Ah, I understand. You mean that while the bot is running, I participate in predictions automatically. Ok, how can I choose the direction of the predict? I mean whether the price will rise or fall, the amount of money I want to bet on the prediction. I don't quite understand this part

Author: Norbert | Ocean#7805
Content:
For setting the stake amount check the envvars.md file from pdr-backend readmes folder. You have to set the environment variable and then the way that is going to be used depends on the chosen approach.
Right now the predicted value is automatically determined by the approach you are choosing. Approach 1 uses random values while Approach 3 uses a dynamic modal which is trained on past price data and predicts the value for you.
If you want to customize the predicted value you can change on of the approaches.

Author: danadalis
Content:
👋**Hey all, I need your help!**

**I'm Daniel from Punch**, a web3 payment provider bridging banks and blockchain. We have been approached by an investment bank that is about to **tokenize a €5B private equity fund** to help protocols diversify their treasury with real-world assets for better risk mitigation. The investment bank needs us to provide a payment solution that works seamlessly between banks and chains.

🤔 **Is this a real problem or just a solution looking for one?**
Before we decide to be part of this, I need to validate these hypotheses:

1. Protocols/Chains/DAOs have the need to diversify their treasury to mitigate risks like asset devaluation.
2. Protocols/Chains/DAOs are interested in diversifying with RWAs such as tokenized private equity funds.

🙏 **I'm searching high and low for experts or those responsible for treasury and strategic investments to help validate this hypothesis.**
Your insights would be invaluable, and I'd be more than happy to share our findings once we've gathered enough data.

❤️ If you can introduce me to the right people or have insights to share, please DM me or reply here.

Cheers,
Daniel

Hello everyone! 😀 

**Introducing the Ocean Data Bounty**
Helping data providers to package, price and market their data.

With the latest version of Ocean Protocol — OceanONDA V4 live, we are announcing a new initiative to accelerate the adoption of Ocean as the orchestration layer for Data and AI. Content:
Hey @Andrea | Ocean Protocol ,

When performing feature selection analysis, do we have to perform ALL the recommended analysis methods (graphical method (times series) & advanced methods (anova, based on correlation, etc.), or we are at liberty to choose between the two methods?

Similarly in the time series analysis, do we have to use the previous graphical methods to identify trends AND develop a model (ARIMA, Prophet, other regressors), or we can choose between the two methods?

Author: doteth
Content:
When performing feature selection analysis, do we have to perform ALL the recommended analysis methods (graphical method (times series) & advanced methods (anova, based on correlation, etc.), or we are at liberty to choose between the two methods? **@user’s discretion**

Similarly in the time series analysis, do we have to use the previous graphical methods to identify trends AND develop a model (ARIMA, Prophet, other regressors), or we can choose between the two methods? **@user’s discretion**

It is stated in the description of the challenge: “You MUST AT LEAST perform the graphical methods described below in order to be considered for the competition.” Does this mean we have to do what is described under ‘Graphical Method’? or it means we can choose to do that which is described as ‘Potential Advanced Methods’ instead? 
**Users must perform at least that. Doing more would potentially give him a higher score.**

Author: 0xblockboy
Content: When looking at the marketplace how do I know if a dataset is updated daily? Because a lot of assets say they are but their metadata history at the bottom will say last updated months ago

Author: nickscavuzzo33
Content: hey @0xBlockBoy  🏴  can you link to the example you are looking at? If it is updated daily then it would show in metadata history, if not it might just be raw dat a

Author: white_rider_
Content: It's not necessarily the case. When the URL points to an endpoint that retrieves data, updates can occur even if the asset's metadata remains the same.

Author: white_rider_
Content: So for example, with a GraphQL published asset, you won't need to modify the asset's metadata to access updated data. When a query is sent to your server, the server can retrieve the most recent data based on the specific query and parameters without the need for metadata changes. This flexibility allows for efficient and dynamic data retrieval while keeping the asset's metadata unchanged.

Author: idiom_bytes
Content:
Yeah, I generally agree. As I mentioned previously alerts and actionable intelligence can be fairly premium.

What I would argue is that not all alerts and not all intelligence is premium.

Example: a stream of stakes, buys, etc... is not very actionable.

Imbalances between DCV and staked amounts are because this is where users can harvest most yield.

In the presentation I provided you, I have alluded to how to build a freemium model that converts users from free, into paying, by slowly increasing the friction and guiding them towards monetization.

Example of a previous arbitrage TG app...
--------
I made most buys/sells alert free. You could access many bot commands that helped users stay engaged and discover the app.

This facilitated the onboarding of thousands of users (no initial friction, more Daily Active Users), and keep them engaged (more user sessions).

However, alerts on arbitrage spreads (I.e. buy on dex1 and sell on dex2 for 5%) and other features were premium because this is where users make money.

This enabled me to obtain many more users (larger funnel due to no friction), while providing them towards a clear path of monetization (obvious value offering/conversion).

Many freemium products offer multiple SKUs (I.e. multiple token gates within a single freemium app). Each token gate (SKU) can be linked to a different feature/super power.

This is where understanding your users segments (different users, different goals) and how to build premium features (solving the customer problem for each segment) within a single freemium product, can lead to much larger revenue.

Hope this helps.

Author: Norbert | Ocean#7805
Content:
So let's say you have 2k OCEAN rewards on your published dataset by wash consume, this means you consumed it in such way in which you payed 2k OCEAN on fees to generate those rewards. For now you are basically on 0.
Now those rewards are distributed between people that allocated to that dataset. Let's say you are the only one allocating 10k veOCEAN, but you are the publisher so you get 20k veOCEAN allocation(2x), great, but still there are 2k OCEAN rewards distributed so you will get 2k OCEAN, not 4k OCEAN.
But, if there are multiple people allocating to your dataset, you will get a greater share of that 2k OCEAN rewards because instead of 10k veOCEAN allocation you have 20k.

Author: djstrikanova
Content:
Hey, I'm part of the Effect DAO which is part of the Effect Network, a blockchain protocol for microtasking on EOS. Effect Network can be used to build datasets with human workers who get paid for completing each tasks in EFX. We're planning a hackathon on DoraHacks with the theme this time around being about creating datasets useful for AI. 

For example, I'm working on a project that collects all NFT's on EOS, downloads their images, and then uses HuggingFace models to generate a caption for them. Then I throw this all into a Search interface that uses ElasticSearch. The idea I have is if you use five different models to generate captions for NFT's you can have workers rate each model 1-10. With enough data you can figure out which models are best for captioning NFTs. You could also generate a lot of good data for potential reinforcement learning down the line for those models too. 

Do you think there is any interest for some collaboration between Ocean Protocol and Effect Network for Effect's hackathon? The general idea would be that participants will build Effect Network programs that generate datasets and the datasets then would be posted to Ocean Protocol's marketplace. If there's interest, let me know who I can contact to set up a connection between them and the Effect Network team.

Author: Norbert | Ocean#7805
Content:
It's not a scam. Initially we used infinite token approval so user doesn't have to approve each time he locks or updates locked amount and save tx fees. Now we removed that feature so user has more control of the amount of approved tokens. If you approved then, you can now use the warning to remove the approval, and only approve the amount you want to lock before locking.
There might also be cases when people approved a large amount but then locked a smaller amount and they have approve tokens left and we advice to remove approval for those for safety reasons.

Author: cesar_cripto
Content: hi! i locked some ocean tokens during 1 month, now this should i delegate to my own wallet address? or how does this step work?

Author: Norbert | Ocean#7805
Content:
Hello 👋 
Delegating it’s only for Volume Active Rewards, and the propose of it is to let other wallet do the allocation of veOCEAN tokens to datasets with good Consume Volume.
If you have multiple wallets and delegate to 1 of them it’s going to be easier to allocate and lower tx fees because all the allocation power is in 1 place.
You can also delegate to a wallet that’s not yours, but be aware that they are going to receive your Volume Rewards and are in charge of sending those to you.

Author: cesar_cripto

Author: Norbert | Ocean#7805
Content:
You don't need to have datasets create in order to allocate, you can allocate to any dataset independent on who published them.
You also don't have to delegate, that's optional. You can easily just allocate to datasets in the table without delegating. 
The delegation is only useful If you want another wallet to manage your allocation, either yours ore someone elses, so you don't have to do it, or you want to do it just once for all your wallets

Author: idiom_bytes
Content:
Hi Damien,

Our base models are currently simple. Only using linear regression, and a single timeframe that you specify... such as 1h timeframe.

**[Overview of how slots/epochs work]**
In this case, we're trying to predict the price at t+1, our dataframe/xY will look like this (1 hour slots/epochs).
```
timestamp  price
00:00:00  1000
00:01:00  1005.?? < this is happening now, so the 1h candle hasn't closed yet
00:02:00  t+1 < what we're predicting for
```

This means that 5m, 15m, and 30m data is not included in the model building.
**This also means that we can't wait for 00:01:00 to close, because we need to submit the prediction for 00:02:00 before the candle closes.**

The best thing you could do here without a lot of work, is to submit predictions for t+1 right before the candle closes, using the current (00:01:00) price.

**predictoor_agent3.py is already implemented to do this.** => https://discord.com/channels/612953348487905282/1184520151912165496/1184895704196468888

Author: idiom_bytes
Content:
Hi Damien, we're in the middle of re-writing a bunch of stuff, pardon me.

I think you're right that the current price is not included in hist_df because the candle hasn't closed yet, so it will not be included.

If you wanted to inject more granular candle data, (but this adds a lot of records, and increases the number of dimensions of your model making it more costly to train/etc...) is to create a dataframe that is composed of 1m + 5m data... whether this improves the performance of the model significantly or not... well, that's part of the exploratory work.

To exemplify this, here is a pseudo df where your implementation would consist of 11 columns:
- 1 for timestamp
- 5 for ohlcv 1m
- 5 for ohlcv 5m

this way, you can a more complete representation of price in a dataframe
```
ts | ohlcv_1m_btc_binance | ohlcv_5m_btc_binance
1 | 1000 | 1000
2 | 1001 | 1000
3 | 1002 | 1000
4 | 1001 | 1000
5 | 1001 | 1000 << 5m candle closes here
6 | 1002 | 1001 << 5m columns would then start using the last 5m ohlcv candle, while 1m columns continue using historical 1m ohlcv candles
```

You are now in the realm of improving model performance, and there are 100 things you can work towards to improving it. Rather than us guessing, there is a lot of literature on the subject. One of the best resources on it today is the book: "Advances in Financial Machine Learning 1st Edition by Marcos Lopez de Prado". I also recommend searching the web as there are many resources and libraries that build upon it.

LMK if you have more questions.

Author: idiom_bytes
Content:
Consider the following 5m epochs
```
t0 < we are here
t1 < next epoch
t2 < epoch we're predicting for
```

Your submissions will be made for epoch t2.
Once t0 closes, you will be unable to submit predictions for t2, as you'll now be submitting a prediction for t3.

```
Are there other ways to lose OCEAN besides losing predictions? Because I have been thinking and figuring out but i should be in profit even though my balance is only decreasing
```

Not quite... but it's important to understand the details... (as laid out in the docs/blogpost linked  by AwesomeQA)

If you predict with 0.5 OCEAN, while others are predicting with 0.1 OCEAN, if you lose, you lose your whole stake... not 0.1.
So, it's important to get a measure for how others are staking such that you're taking the right amount of risk.

We're working towards building more tooling around this such that it's easier for predictoors to monitor and improve their stake. TBD.

Author: idiom_bytes
Content:
1. Good, the latest prices are included.
2. The model/system we're building is designed to re-train/build/predict on the fly. Please be mindful of this as training/deploying something on the cloud (or even locally) will change the behavior we're designing for.

This will evolve in the future... I.e. build/cache/re-use model for 10 epochs.

As you probably know, trained models can drift in performance, and managing ML models is a practice on its own.

3. The predictor agent has been designed to make multiple submissions in the last 60s.

Why?
- each prediction will have different data as p1 will have the latest_price up to the last 60s. Then p2 will be up to the last 30s. Finally p3 might have most of the last candle data, up-to-the very end of the epoch.

Look at pdr_trader for how to cache/check if you've already submitted a prediction for an epoch if you only want to submit once... Again, please be mindful of the example I gave above as to why we do this as the default behavior.

4. Make sure that your bot submitted something first, then run the script against the right network and that your start/end times look good.

If you are still having issues, try running this subgraph query in our sapphire subgraph directly to see if you can find any of the predictions you have submitted for in the past: https://github.com/oceanprotocol/pdr-backend/blob/5c1a67796c680c610111cd238005f639d298d5f3/pdr_backend/util/subgraph_predictions.py#L23

Again, double check that you are running the query against the right subgraph (testnet vs. mainnet)

rather than have 1 app w/ 10 predictoors,

Author: idiom_bytes
Content:
You can also do what you're doing, but the bot will...
1st, try to submit a prediction for BTC
2nd, try to submit a prediction for ETH
3rd, try to submit a prediction for DOGE

Because the bot starts submitting predictions 60s before the deadline, by the 4th prediction (example... ADA/USDT), you'll run out of time and won't be able to submit to other feeds

To use Ocean Predictoor, follow these steps:

Author: ndubss
Content:
Running multiple predictoor bots in Ocean Protocol involves some limitations and complexities, but there are potential workarounds depending on your needs and risk tolerance. Here's what you need to know:

 Challenges and Limitations:

Security: Using multiple bots with the same wallet increases your attack surface, as each bot needs access to private keys and could potentially drain funds. This is the biggest concern.
API Key Restrictions: Depending on the platform you use to connect your bots, API key limitations might hinder running multiple bots simultaneously.
Exchange Restrictions: Some cryptocurrency exchanges impose limitations on the number of bots or API keys allowed per account.
Complexity: Managing and coordinating multiple bots with different strategies can be challenging and susceptible to unintended consequences.
 Potential Workarounds:

Multiple Wallets: This is the safest option, requiring separate wallets for each bot with unique private keys. However, managing multiple wallets effectively adds complexity and requires strong security practices.
Single Bot with Strategy Switching: Develop a single bot capable of switching between different prediction strategies based on defined parameters. This offers flexibility while maintaining control in one place.
Testnets and Simulations: Utilize platforms like Ocean Testnet or other simulations to test your bots and strategies without risking real funds. This is recommended before deploying bots on the mainnet.
Cloud Providers and Virtual Machines: Explore advanced setups using cloud providers like AWS or Azure to create isolated virtual machines for each bot, potentially improving security but requiring technical expertise.
 Disclaimer:

Due to the inherent security risks, running multiple bots on the same wallet is generally not recommended.
Carefully consider the risks and legal implications in your region before using bots for trading.
Thoroughly research and understand the limitations and complexity involved before attempting any workaround.
Never share your private keys or seed phrases with any bot or program.

Author: sarahsweetchilli
Content: Is there any platform for non-techy users to contribute to datasets or aggregate / annotate data?

Author: sarahsweetchilli
Content:
*Example:* I'm a non-techy person with a lot of pictures on my phone and I want to make money from this data. 

*Another Example* I am a person with spare time, who isn't familiar with AI or machine learning, and I want to make side money from data annotation or data generation (these are repetitive and simple jobs once the fundamentals are laid down)

Author: sarahsweetchilli
Content: Right now the people selling datasets are people who have already aggregated and annotated data. To my knowledge most of these people are business managers, crypto nerds or AI experts. Nothing wrong with this, it's just a niche audience.

Author: sarahsweetchilli
Content: Ocean could appeal to the entire world, rather than just experts, if we make data annotation accessible & profitable for the average person. If we build dApps that allow normal people to upload + annotate data in their spare time and make a bit of cash whilst doing it--say, they can draw bounding boxes around pictures from their phones--we would increase Ocean's fundamental value whilst creating casual jobs.

Author: sarahsweetchilli
Content: Forgive me if anything I've said is wrong or ignorant, I'm still learning. I have had this idea for a while and I think you guys would like to hear it. If such a dApp is already being developed, let me know. If not, I would like to start on something

Author: sarahsweetchilli

Author: sarahsweetchilli
robinlehmann
Content:
If you calculate in the costs for swapping USDT -> ETH or BNT (if you use Bancor) -> OCEAN via DEXes or the cost for USDT -> OCEAN on Binance you get a price that would be equivalent to USD.
But in general this could be seen as a temporal problem as there will probably soon be options to just pay with USD. Just a matter of time and adoption.
For DataUnion.app we will (at some point) have offramps to BTC, USDT, USD, EUR etc. and probably also onramps as this basically enables more consumers and contributors to consume/participate in the dataset.

Author: robinlehmann
Content:
Ocean Protocol is not available on the NEAR blockchain, so that would be the first thing that would be a collaboration - make it possible to use Ocean Protocol on NEAR. NEAR promises to deliver scalability and low cost transactions on its blockchain but also a compatibility with Ethereum via their Rainbow bridge.
It would be a great collaboration to make it possible that the project is usable on both blockchains.
After that the data collection can be done and offered on both blockchains at the same time.
That would be my initial thoughts about NEAR and Ocean synergies.

Author: robinlehmann
Content:
A few questions to help us help you - how long will the video be?
I saw your previous video and from what I understand the platform you are using to create them is providing you with images/objects and effects to create the video, right?

What is Ocean?
This is covered well by the Mission statement of Ocean here:
https://oceanprotocol.com/about

From my point of view the core components of Ocean Protocol have been created in the past - namely: marketplaces, compute-to-data and datatokens as well as the beginning of the OceanDAO. This can all be used to enhance Data Science.
That are the achievements.

What is still outstanding from the technical point of view is the integration of compute-to-data into the marketplace itself.
The only thing that is publicly know about it can be found in the roadmap of Ocean: https://oceanprotocol.com/roadmap
Quote:

In Ocean Market: buy & sell private data while preserving privacy
Mitigates risk of buyer-supplied malicious algorithms, via whitelisted algorithms or workflow for publisher to vet algorithms

To me this means that data can be sold without having to leave the storage of the data provider. Also that this data cannot be copied by the buyer.
But that the compute done by the algorithms are also covered by the data provider via their hardware. And that the data buyer will pay for this compute.
